title: For Sale:  Rare Lend/Lease 1911 From WW2 Nearly Mint Condition
postcontent:
Thinning out some of my collection to fund some other purchases. I bought this lend/lease marked 1911 several years ago because it was unlike anyhting I had ever encountered, and I collect a lot of 1911 variants. This 1911's frame, serial 408211, began life as a Colt in 1918 for WW1. At some point in it's service life, between then and WW2, the slide became damaged and the pistol ended up at Augusta Arsenal. There it was fitted with a new Remington slide, High Standard barrel, a few A1 parts including the grips, and parkerized. Now here's where it gets interesting. From there the pistol was sent to England as part of our lend/lease program. You'll find the British proof marks on the barrel, slide, and frame. Due to the incredible condition of the finish, it is unlikely that the pistol was ever issued upon being received and accepted by England.
The parkerized finish is uniform throughout the pistol with little to no wear to be found. The only slight sign of wear is found on the right side of the trigger. The barrel's finish is blued and there's bits of cosmoline in the rifling. The bore overall looks brand new. The frame bears the 'United States Property' mark as well as 'AA' for Augusta Arsenal and the English acceptance stamp. The slide displays the English acceptance stamp as well as the standard Remington Rand hallmarks and a P on the top of the slide.
This truly is a unique piece of history. A frame that saw both World Wars and proof marks that it was sent to our ally Britian to aid in the fight against Germany. And to top of that off, it's in fantastic condition. Since ArmsList will only allow a few photos please refer to the below DropBox link for the a gallery of high-resolution photos. If you have any questions or would like to see additional pics of anything just let me know. Please respond via email and I will get back to you quickly. I am not a FFL holder however I would be happy to ship the pistol provided you make arrangements with an FFL in your state that can receive it and transfer it to yourself.Asking $1500 however I will entertain realistic offers. Not interested in any trades at this time so please do not ask.

Thanks!If the ad is still up, the item is still available. I will remove the ad when it sells like everyone should do on every listing anyway. CPL holders always prefered. All firearms sales (serialized parts) will require a bill of sale AND RI-060 transfer for handguns. This is only done as a measure of protection for both parties. This is something you should welcome in an honest transaction. The registration paperwork and bill of sale on handguns is not negotiable. If you read this and are still interested and have any questions, please let me know.Please, be able to have an intelligent conversation about pricing, values, basic guns and ammo information and item descriptions. I try to list everything of importance in my ads and do not want to have a week long back and forth discussion because you cannot articulate an acceptable explanation of your items or questions about my items. If you refer to magazines as clips, cartridges as boolets or send photos of your guns with your finger on the trigger, I will assume we are off to a less than desirable start. Sorry if I sound rude, but I have bought and sold a fair amount from Armslist and the sheer amount of people that cannot seem to follow the golden four rules of firearms safety or use correct terminology is an ongoing issue. It is an ongoing issue across the entire firearms culture for some reason and every one of us should be working to do better.If you want to test fire a gun that I am selling, that is perfectly acceptable in most cases. I am happy to meet with you at COSC on a weekend with you as my guest or at a range of your choosing at your own expense.Thank you for looking! Check out my "Listings by this user" link to the right of the photo above for a look at all of my listed items! I am always listing new items and may not have something posted yet.
